item.caption: HEMOGLOBIN A1C - Final result (02/16/2012 11:57 AM PST)
TESTOSTERONE (TESTOSTERONE, TOTAL) - Final result (02/16/2012 11:57 AM PST)

content.content:
Early AM (6 - 9 AM) Testosterone levels are usually 10 - 30 % higher than
PM levels in younger men (under 50 years).
Early morning specimen collection is strongly preferred for determining
androgen status in men. Interfering substances may cause false elevations
in testosterone immunoassays at low concentrations. Consider ordering
Testosterone, Total, Pediatric (EAP# 84403G), or for adults, order
Testosterone, Ultrasensitive by LC/MSMS (EAP# 84403K). These tests are
performed at Quest Laboratories and are appropriate for pediatric patients,
adult females, and adult males undergoing testosterone suppression therapy.

item.caption: GLUCOSE (GLUCOSE, RANDOM) - Final result (02/16/2012 11:57 AM PST)

content.content:
Borderline range of 160 - 199 mg/dL suggests follow-up. Results greater
than or equal to 200 mg/dL is suggestive of diabetes in the setting of
classical symptoms.

item.caption: CREATININE AND CALCULATED GLOMERULAR FILTRATION RATE (CREATININE, SERUM, WITH GLOMERULAR FILTRATION RATE, CALCULATED) - Final result (02/16/2012 11:57 AM PST)

content.content:
Glomerular Filtration Rate (GFR) estimate is expressed in mL/min/1.73 m2
body surface area. A GFR estimate is validated only for patients greater
than or equal to 18 years of age. Since this test is not useful if renal
function is changing rapidly, a GFR estimate is not reported for inpatients.
Many elderly patients have mildly to moderately reduced GFR.
Per K/DOQI Clinical Practice Guidelines on Chronic Kidney Disease:
GFR 30 - 59 = Stage 3 CKD
GFR 15 - 29 = Stage 4 CKD
GFR < 15 = Stage 5 CKD
